	    "Alas, sir, how fell you besides your five wits?&quot;
Malvolio: &quot;Fool, there was never a man so notoriously abused. I am as well in my wits, fool, as thou art.&quot;
Feste: &quot;But as well? Then you are mad indeed, if you be no better in you wits than a fool." -- William Shakespeare

	    "But, indeed, words are very rascals, since bonds [vows] disgraced them.&quot;
Viola: &quot;Thy reason, man?&quot;
Feste: &quot;Troth [Truthfully], sir, I can yield you none without words, and words are grown so false, I am loathe to prove reason with them." -- William Shakespeare

	    "So the little prince tamed the fox. And when the hour of his departure drew near--

Ah,&quot; said the fox, &quot;I shall cry.&quot;

It is your own fault,&quot; said the little prince. &quot;I never wished you any sort of harm; but you wanted me to tame you . . .&quot;

Yes, that is so,&quot; said the fox.

But now you are going to cry!&quot; said the little prince.

Yes, that is so,&quot; said the fox.

Then it has done you no good at all!&quot;

It has done me good,&quot; said the fox, &quot;because of the color of the wheat fields." -- Antoine de Saint-Exupéry
